Task 1 - Introductory Questions

1) If we have the following model to explain the revenue of a company: \[\log(Revenue) = \beta_0 + \beta_1 Industry + \beta_2 InitialInvestment + \beta_3 (InitialInvestment)^2 + \beta_4 CEOExperience + \varepsilon\] Which of the following statements is/are TRUE?(4 points)

  1. The association between CEO experience and revenue is not constant and changes depending on the CEO’s initial experience, holding industry and initial investment constant.

  2. Revenue and Initial Investment will be positively correlated (holding other variables constant) if \(\beta_2\) is positive.

  3. If \(\beta_3\) is not statistically significant, we cannot argue that there is a quadratic relationship between revenue and initial investment.

  4. \(\beta_0\) represents the average revenue when all other covariates are set to 0.

  5. If \(\beta_3<0\), it is evidence that there are diminishing returns to initial investment on revenue, holding other variables constant.

Answer:

C and E

2) You are working in revenue management for an airline, and need to decide whether to apply a promotion for a specific route in the following week. This promotion would decrease prices by 15% in that route for all customers. Your outcome of interest, PriceIncrease, is whether your sales increase that week (1) or not (0) with respect to the previous one.

You remember your causal inference training and decide to put it into practice. In this case, which are your potential outcomes?(2 points)

  1. PriceIncrease=1 and PriceIncrease=0.

  2. PriceIncrease=1 if I apply the discount, PriceIncrease=0 if I apply the discount, PriceIncrease=1 if I don’t apply the discount, PriceIncrease=0 if I don’t apply the discount.

  3. PriceIncrease if I apply the discount, PriceIncrease if I don’t apply the discount.

  4. PriceIncrease=1 and PriceIncrease=0 if I apply the discount.

Answer:

C

3) Which of the following statements represent the fundamental problem of causal inference? Select all that apply (2 points)

  1. “If we want to know the effect of a marketing campaign, we cannot observe what would have happened if we hadn’t put it in place”

  2. “We cannot generalize the findings from a small sample to a larger population, because most of the time, they are not representative”

  3. “In social sciences, we cannot observe individual causal effects”

  4. “Traditional regressions impose a linear functional form that it is not usually realistic”

Answer:

A and C

4) Which of the following statements is/are NOT TRUE regarding Linear Probability Models (LPM)? (4 points)


a) An LPM is a traditional linear regression with a binary outcome
b) LPM performs better than logistic regressions are prediction because they are simpler.
c) The intercept in a LPM captures the average probability of an event happening (Y=1) for my entire sample.
d) Generally, we shouldn’t use LPM if we have small samples.

Answer: B and C

5) Thinking about the following model:

\[\log\left(Income\right)=\beta_0+\beta_1CollegeMajor+\beta_2SAT+\beta_3ParentsIncome+\varepsilon\]

Is the following interpretation of \(\beta_2\) TRUE? (2 points)

“One additional point in the SAT is associated with a \(\beta_2\times100\) percentage point increase in income, holding college major and parental income constant”.

Answer:

Additionally, create a new price variable names price000s that measures price in thousands of dollars (instead of dollars). How many observations do we have left? (Note: Use unformattedPrice to have a numeric version of price) (1 points)

2) You know that the size of a house is clearly associated to price, but you don’t think that relationship is linear. Fit a model that captures a quadratic relationship between area and price (no need to include additional covariates).

a) Show your code for the regression previously discussed. Include the code for dropping variables and creating price000s (from 2.1). (2 points)

Answer:

austin_clean <- austin %>% filter(!is.na(area) & !is.na(unformattedPrice))
austin_clean <- austin_clean %>% mutate(price000s = unformattedPrice/1000)

lm_quad <- lm(price000s ~ area + I(area^2), data = austin_clean)

summary(lm_quad)

4) Create a scatter plot for price (Y) and area (X), clearly identifying the previous outliers. Include a quadratic regression line for the complete sample and another quadratic regression line for the sample without outliers.

Hint: You will have to use geom_smooth(method = “lm”) to include this linear regression, and should look into the “formula” argument to see how to add a quadratic line. Use ?geom_smooth() help to find some answers!

Answer:

# One way
ggplot(data = austin_clean, aes(y = price000s, x = area, color = factor(outlier))) + 
  geom_point() + theme_minimal() +
  xlab("Area (sqft)") + ylab("Price (M$)") +
  scale_color_manual("Outliers", values = c("skyblue3","purple"), labels = c("No","Yes")) +
  geom_smooth(method = 'lm',formula = y ~ poly(x, 2), color = "purple", se = FALSE) +
  geom_smooth(data = austin_wo_outliers, aes(y = price000s, x = area),
              method = 'lm',formula = y ~ poly(x, 2), color = "blue", se = FALSE) +
  annotate("text", label = "Without outliers", x = 6800, y = 10500, color = "blue") + #Add annotations to the plot
  annotate("text", label = "With outliers", x = 12200, y = 10000, color = "purple")

# Another way
ggplot(data = austin_clean, aes(y = price000s, x = area)) + 
  geom_point(aes(fill = factor(outlier)), pch = 21, color = alpha("darkgrey",0)) + theme_minimal() +
  xlab("Area (sqft)") + ylab("Price (M$)") +
  scale_fill_manual("Outliers", values = c("skyblue3","purple"), labels = c("No","Yes")) +
  geom_smooth(aes(color = "With outliers"), method = 'lm',formula = y ~ poly(x, 2), se = FALSE) +
  geom_smooth(data = austin_wo_outliers, aes(y = price000s, x = area, color = "Without outliers"),
              method = 'lm',formula = y ~ poly(x, 2), se = FALSE) +
  scale_color_manual("Quad lines", values = c("purple","blue"), labels = c("With outliers","Without outliers"))


10 points: Creates the correct plot including: (1) highlights outliers vs non-outliers, (2) creates two quadratic regression lines (different colors), (3) uses correct labels for the axis, and (4) has at least one appropriate legend (for outliers or the lines).

6 points: Problems with two of the previous items.

4 points: Problems with three of the previous items.

0 point: Problems with all four items.

Task 3 - Targeting donations

You are working for a non-profit organization and you are in charge of getting donations. You are asked to target potential donors that make over $50,000 in income, and they provide a dataset of potential donors:

donors <- read.csv("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/maibennett/sta235/main/exampleSite/content/Assignments/Homework/HW2/data/income.csv")

Some of the variables in the dataset are the following:

  • age: Age in years
  • workclass: Games played.
  • education: Education (highest level)
  • education_num: Education (years)
  • marital_status: Marital status
  • occupation: Occupation (category)
  • race: Race (category)
  • gender: Gender (male or female)
  • hours_per_week: Hours worked in a week
  • native_country: Country of birth
  • income_over_50k: Income is greater than $50k or equal or less than $50k

1a) Create a binary variable for income \(> \%50k\) (1) and \(\leq\$50k\) (0), called income50. (2 points)

Answer:

donors <- donors %>% mutate(income50 = ifelse(income_over_50k==">50K", 1, 0))

donors %>% select(income50) %>% table(.)

0 points: Does not create the variable correctly

2a) Create a categorical variable (factor variable), called race3, that has three categories: (1) White, (2) Black, and (3) All others. In this case, all observations that are not in the first or second category should be in the third one. Hint: You can create first a numeric variable, and then transform that into a factor variable. Don’t forget to use labels for your factor variable! (6 points)

Answer:

donors <- donors %>% mutate(race3 = ifelse(race=="White",1,
                                           ifelse(race=="Black",2,3))) %>%

donors %>% select(race3) %>% table(.)
